/*
Problem: Upper Bound

Definition:
Return the index of the first element greater than x.
If no such element exists, return n.

Approach:
1. Initialize answer as n.
2. Apply Binary Search.
3. If nums[mid] > x:
   - Store mid as a potential answer.
   - Search on the left side for a smaller valid index.
4. Otherwise, search on the right side.
5. Return the answer.

Time Complexity: O(log N)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int upperBound(vector<int> &nums, int x) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;
        int ans = n;

        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] > x) {
                ans = mid;
                end = mid - 1;
            } else {
                st = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Mistakes I Made While Learning:

1. Used:
   nums[mid] >= x
   Correct:
   nums[mid] > x
   (Upper Bound finds the first element strictly greater than x.)

2. Updated both pointers in the same if block:
   end = mid - 1;
   st = mid + 1;
   Correct:
   Move only one pointer based on the condition.

3. Wrote:
   start = mid + 1;
   Correct:
   st = mid + 1;

4. Forgot the else block.
   Binary Search always follows:
   if (condition) {
       // save answer
       // search left
   } else {
       // search right
   }

Key Difference:

Lower Bound -> First element >= x
Upper Bound -> First element > x

Binary Search Rule:
Left Search  -> end = mid - 1;
Right Search -> st = mid + 1;
*/

